title: [Node] console.dir() options
body:
According to source code the ``console.dir()`` method [takes the same options][latestsrcdir] that ``util.inspect()`` does: 
```js
Console.prototype.dir = function dir(object, options) {
  options = Object.assign({customInspect: false}, options);
  write(this._ignoreErrors,
        this._stdout,
        `${util.inspect(object, options)}\n`, // <--- attention here 
        this._stdoutErrorHandler);
};

```
The ``options`` object from above is left intact and passed down to the ``inspect()`` call hence leading to idea that the options interfaces of both methods ``console.dir()`` and ``inspect()`` are the same and have to be unified.  This unification is done by this PR.

Here some links on source code and docs of ``console.dir()`` to be sure:

- [``console.dir()``][v012srcdir]	  of NodeJS **v0.x**
- [``console.dir()``][v4srcdir]     of NodeJS **v4.x**
- [``console.dir()``][v6srcdir]     of NodeJS **v6.x**
- [``console.dir()``][latestsrcdir] and [docs][latestDocsDir] of NodeJS **v8.x**

## Changes
### Node v8x, v6x, v4x, v0
The same fixes were done across all nodejs declaration versions to ensure consistency.
-  Moves up ``InspectOptions`` from ``util`` module to ``NodeJS`` namespace
- Leaves mocking interface ``InspectOptions`` inside ``util``

### Node v0
- Resurrect missing ``console`` declaration 
(seems like somebody forgot or intentionally left it undeclared :neutral_face: )
